Make touch-driven panning scroll on the async scrolling thread instead of
being forced synchronous (main-thread) whenever the touched region carries a
non-passive wheel/mousewheel listener.

Background
----------
WPE already has the full threaded async-scrolling stack compiled in and enabled
(ENABLE_ASYNC_SCROLLING + ENABLE_SCROLLING_THREAD via PlatformEnableGlib,
ThreadedScrollingCoordinator / ScrollingTreeCoordinated, the live "Core:Scrolling"
thread, and ENABLE_KINETIC_SCROLLING). Touch panning is turned into synthetic
"smooth" wheel/axis events by TouchGestureController; those events carry precise
scrolling deltas (hasPreciseScrollingDeltas == true).

The keystone that defeats it: ScrollingTree::computeWheelProcessingSteps() returns
{ SynchronousScrolling, BlockingDOMEventDispatch } for the *first* event of a
gesture as soon as the scroll point lies in a synchronous wheel/mousewheel
tracking region (i.e. any non-passive wheel/mousewheel listener under the finger,
which modern SPAs like reddit attach to feed/post elements). WHEEL_EVENT_REGIONS
(the NonBlocking-gesture-state escape hatch) is compiled OUT on WPE, so there is
no way back to async. Because the first event goes to the main thread, no async
scroll ever starts, isUserScrollInProgressAtEventLocation() stays false, and
EventDispatcher keeps every subsequent event synchronous too. Result on device:
the Core:Scrolling thread is idle (~0.5%) while the WebProcess main thread is
pegged (~33%) and scrolling crawls at ~7fps. Because the events never reach the
scrolling thread's ScrollingEffectsController, the kinetic (fling) animation
never runs either, so there is no momentum.

Fix
---
For precise-delta (touch / touchpad) wheel events, treat a synchronous wheel
region the way other ports treat a NonBlocking gesture state: scroll
asynchronously on the scrolling thread and still dispatch the DOM wheel event,
but non-blocking (the page's listener still fires, it just can't block the
scroll). This mirrors the passive-listener behaviour the browser already forces
via its kPassiveScroll user script, and matches how mobile WebKit keeps touch
panning off the main thread. Discrete mouse-wheel events (no precise deltas) are
unaffected and keep their existing synchronous/blocking behaviour.

Gated on WEBKIT_TOUCH_SCROLL_ASYNC (default ON; set =0 to restore upstream
behaviour for A/B testing on device, like the other tuning env patches).
--- a/Source/WebCore/page/scrolling/ScrollingTree.cpp
+++ b/Source/WebCore/page/scrolling/ScrollingTree.cpp
@@ -46,10 +46,31 @@
 #include <wtf/TZoneMallocInlines.h>
 #include <wtf/text/TextStream.h>
 
+#include <cstdlib>
+#include <cstring>
+
 namespace WebCore {
 
 WTF_MAKE_TZONE_ALLOCATED_IMPL(ScrollingTree);
 
+// When a touch (or touchpad) pan lands on a synchronous wheel/mousewheel
+// tracking region, scroll it asynchronously on the scrolling thread instead of
+// dropping to the main thread. The DOM wheel event is still dispatched, just
+// non-blocking, so page listeners fire without blocking the scroll. Keeps touch
+// panning smooth (and lets the kinetic/fling animation run) on SPAs that attach
+// non-passive wheel listeners. See webkit-touch-async-scroll-env.patch.
+static bool touchAsyncScrollEnabled()
+{
+    static bool enabled = [] {
+        const char* env = getenv("WEBKIT_TOUCH_SCROLL_ASYNC");
+        // Default ON; only an explicit "0" disables it.
+        if (env && *env)
+            return strcmp(env, "0") != 0;
+        return true;
+    }();
+    return enabled;
+}
+
 using OrphanScrollingNodeMap = HashMap<ScrollingNodeID, RefPtr<ScrollingTreeNode>>;
 
 struct CommitTreeState {
@@ -114,8 +135,16 @@
             || m_treeState.eventTrackingRegions.trackingTypeForPoint(EventTrackingRegions::EventType::Mousewheel, roundedPosition) == TrackingType::Synchronous;
         LOG_WITH_STREAM(Scrolling, stream << "\nScrollingTree::computeWheelProcessingSteps: wheelEvent " << wheelEvent << " mapped to content point " << position << ", in non-fast region " << isSynchronousDispatchRegion);
 
-        if (isSynchronousDispatchRegion)
+        if (isSynchronousDispatchRegion) {
+            // Touch / touchpad panning (precise deltas) stays on the scrolling
+            // thread even over a non-passive wheel region: scroll async and
+            // dispatch the DOM wheel event non-blocking, so listeners still fire
+            // but cannot block the scroll. Discrete wheel events are unchanged.
+            if (touchAsyncScrollEnabled() && wheelEvent.hasPreciseScrollingDeltas())
+                return { WheelEventProcessingSteps::AsyncScrolling, WheelEventProcessingSteps::NonBlockingDOMEventDispatch };
+
             return { WheelEventProcessingSteps::SynchronousScrolling, WheelEventProcessingSteps::BlockingDOMEventDispatch };
+        }
     }
 
 #if ENABLE(WHEEL_EVENT_REGIONS)
